            <!-- Rich Text Body -->
            <div class="prose max-w-none" x-show="lang === 'zh'">
                <p>新品上架 TikTok Shop，最怕的不是产品没人看到，而是素材测完一圈还是跑不动。冷启动阶段的核心任务，是在最短时间内找到跑量素材，然后把预算快速集中过去。很多团队在这个环节犯了“广撒网”或者“一条素材死磕”两个极端的错误。下面用六个问答，拆解冷启动期素材池搭建的正确思路。</p>
<h2>一、冷启动期至少要准备多少条素材？</h2>
<p>最低有效素材量是 15-20 条。这里的“有效”指的是不同脚本方向、不同镜头语言，而非同一套素材换个字幕。</p>
<p>判断标准是：如果一个素材三天内 CPM 超过 15 美元且没有任何转化信号，这条素材基本可以判定为低效。冷启动期需要足够的素材数量来对冲这种筛选损耗。某家居品类卖家曾在冷启动阶段只准备了 5 条素材，全部低效后陷入被动，等新素材补齐已浪费近两周时间。</p>
<h2>二、素材类型怎么配比才合理？</h2>
<p>冷启动阶段建议按 4:3:3 配比：</p>
<ul>
<li>40% 产品展示类：直接展示使用场景，突出 1-2 个核心卖点</li>
<li>30% UGC 真实体验类：素人口播或开箱，强调真实感</li>
<li>30% 测试类素材：尝试剧情、对比、痛点等非常规形式</li>
</ul>
<p>前两类是基本盘，后一类是寻找爆款的探索仓位。不要在冷启动阶段把全部精力放在制作一条“完美素材”上，平台算法更看重素材的更迭速度和测试广度。</p>
<h2>三、素材的测试周期应该怎么设定？</h2>
<p>单条素材给 48-72 小时观察窗口，CPM 和 CTR 两个指标优先于转化率。</p>
<p>判断标准：<br />
- CPM 持续高于类目均值 2 倍以上 → 暂停<br />
- CTR 低于 0.5% 且三天内没有改善趋势 → 暂停<br />
- 有转化但 ROAS 低于 1.5 → 降低预算观察，不要立刻关停</p>
<p>很多团队因为过度关注前两天的转化数据而误杀素材。冷启动期算法还在学习人群包，前 48 小时的转化数据往往不稳定。</p>
<h2>四、UGC 素材的比例该占多少？</h2>
<p>冷启动期 UGC 占比建议不低于 40%。</p>
<p>TikTok 的流量分发逻辑更偏向真实用户创作的内容，搬运式产品广告在冷启动阶段天然处于劣势。找到与目标市场匹配的真实用户拍摄素材，或者用“半真实感”脚本（素人出镜但有脚本引导），往往比精制的品牌广告起量更快。</p>
<p>例外情况：客单价超过 150 美元的高客单产品，UGC 的说服力可能不足，需要增加产品细节展示和信任背书类素材的比重。</p>
<h2>五、账户结构应该怎么设计来配合素材测试？</h2>
<p>建议采用“一产品多广告组”结构：</p>
<ul>
<li>每个产品单独建 Campaign</li>
<li>Campaign 下设 3-5 个 Ad Set，按人群或兴趣标签区分</li>
<li>每个 Ad Set 至少 3 条不同素材</li>
</ul>
<p>这样设计的目的是在同一产品下隔离测试不同素材，避免算法把所有预算压到一条表现稍好的素材上。如果预算有限（每日低于 200 美元），可以把多个产品合并到同一个 Campaign，用 Ad Set 区分产品，节省账户结构成本。</p>
<h2>六、预算在素材间怎么分配最有效？</h2>
<p>冷启动期不要做平均分配。</p>
<p>推荐操作方式：</p>
<ol>
<li>首批 5 条素材各给 20% 预算，观察 48 小时</li>
<li>表现最好的 1-2 条素材追加 50% 预算</li>
<li>低效素材降低到最低预算线（通常是 5 美元/天）继续跑，测试是否有转化后反弹</li>
<li>新素材持续补充进池子，保持总数不低于 15 条</li>
</ol>
<p>核心原则是：让数据说话，而不是让审美判断主导预算分配。</p>
<h2>写在最后</h2>
<p>TikTok Shop 冷启动的本质是快速试错、快速迭代。素材池不是一次性建好的，而是在测试中不断淘汰和补充的动态资产。把“找到跑量素材”设为唯一目标，其他动作都围绕这个目标展开，预算利用率才会最大化。</p>
            </div>
            <div class="prose max-w-none" x-show="lang === 'en'" x-cloak>
                <p>When launching a new product on TikTok Shop, the biggest fear isn't lack of visibility — it's running through your ad creatives and still seeing no traction. At the cold launch stage, the core mission is finding high-performing creatives as quickly as possible and concentrating budget there. Many teams fall into two extremes: spreading budget too thin across dozens of low-quality creatives, or doubling down on a single piece of content that refuses to convert.</p>
<h2>How many creatives do you need for a cold launch?</h2>
<p>The minimum viable number is 15-20 unique creatives. "Unique" here means different script directions and visual approaches, not the same video with a new caption.</p>
<p>The benchmark: if a creative has a CPM above $15 for three days with zero conversion signals, it's likely underperforming. Cold launches require enough creative volume to absorb this screening process. One home goods seller who prepared only 5 creatives for cold launch ended up wasting nearly two weeks waiting for new assets to arrive after all five underperformed.</p>
<h2>What is the optimal creative type mix?</h2>
<p>A 4:3:3 ratio works best for cold launches:</p>
<ul>
<li>40% product showcase: direct usage scenarios with 1-2 core selling points highlighted</li>
<li>30% UGC authentic experience: real user testimonials or unboxing emphasizing authenticity</li>
<li>30% experimental creatives: drama, comparisons, pain-point scenarios, or unconventional formats</li>
</ul>
<p>The first two categories form your baseline; the third represents your exploration zone for potential breakout hits. Avoid spending all your energy crafting one "perfect" ad. The TikTok algorithm rewards creative turnover and testing breadth over production polish.</p>
<h2>How should you set the testing window for each creative?</h2>
<p>Give each creative a 48-72 hour observation window, prioritizing CPM and CTR over direct conversion metrics.</p>
<p>Decision thresholds:</p>
<ul>
<li>CPM stays 2x above category average → pause</li>
<li>CTR below 0.5% with no improvement trend over three days → pause</li>
<li>Some conversions but ROAS below 1.5 → reduce budget for observation, don't immediately shut down</li>
</ul>
<p>Many teams mistakenly kill creatives based on the first two days of conversion data. During cold launch, the algorithm is still learning the audience profile, so early conversion signals are often unstable.</p>
<h2>What percentage of your creatives should be UGC?</h2>
<p>UGC should make up at least 40% of your cold launch creative pool.</p>
<p>TikTok's traffic distribution inherently favors content that feels like authentic user creation rather than polished product advertising. Finding real users in your target market to film, or using "semi-authentic" scripts (real-looking talent with light direction) typically launches faster than studio-quality brand ads.</p>
<p>Exception: for high-ticket items above $150, UGC alone may lack persuasion power. Increase the proportion of product detail and trust-building creatives.</p>
<h2>How should you structure your ad accounts to support creative testing?</h2>
<p>Use a "one product, multiple ad sets" structure:</p>
<ul>
<li>Create a separate Campaign for each product</li>
<li>Within each Campaign, set up 3-5 Ad Sets segmented by audience or interest targeting</li>
<li>Run at least 3 different creatives in each Ad Set</li>
</ul>
<p>This structure isolates creative testing for the same product, preventing the algorithm from funneling all budget into one marginally better creative. If your budget is tight (below $200/day), consolidate multiple products into one Campaign and use Ad Sets to differentiate them.</p>
<h2>What is the most effective way to allocate budget across creatives?</h2>
<p>Don't split budget evenly during cold launch.</p>
<p>Recommended approach:</p>
<ol>
<li>Divide initial budget across 5 creatives at 20% each, observe for 48 hours</li>
<li>Add 50% more budget to the top 1-2 performers</li>
<li>Reduce underperformers to minimum budget (typically $5/day) and continue monitoring for potential late-stage recovery</li>
<li>Continuously add new creatives to the pool, maintaining at least 15 total</li>
</ol>
<p>Core principle: let data guide budget decisions, not subjective aesthetic judgments. The fastest path to a successful TikTok Shop cold launch is rapid iteration — finding what works and scaling it while you continue testing alternatives.</p>
